{{Infobox venue | name = Ben Meyer Diamond at Ray E. Didier Field | nickname = | image = [[File:Ray E. Didier Field (Thibodaux, Louisiana) marquee.jpg|300px]] | fullname = | former_names = | location = [[Thibodaux, Louisiana]], United States | coordinates = {{coord|29|47|10|N|90|48|08|W|type:landmark_region:US-LA|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1960 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Nicholls State University]] | operator = [[Nicholls Colonels|Nicholls Athletics Department]] | surface = Natural [[grass]] | scoreboard = Electronic | estimated_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 3,200 | record_attendance = | executive_suites = | dimensions = 331 ft. ([[Left field|LF]]), 400 ft. ([[Baseball field#outfield|CF]]), 331 ft. ([[Right field|RF]]) | acreage = | tenants = [[Nicholls Colonels baseball]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) }}
'''Ben Meyer Diamond at Ray E. Didier Field''' is a [[baseball]] venue in [[Thibodaux, Louisiana]], United States.<ref>{{cite web| title=Nicholls State University Baseball|publisher=geauxcolonels.com|url=http://www.geauxcolonels.com/sports/2010/6/28/BB_0628100436.aspx?path=baseball|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nicholls State releases Schedule|publisher=collegebaseballdaily.com|url=http://www.collegebaseballdaily.com/2014/12/10/nicholls-state-releases-2015-schedule/|accessdate=2015-09-07}}</ref> It is home to the [[Nicholls Colonels baseball]] team of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Southland Conference]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Southland’s top two pitching staffs battle at Ray E. Didier Field|publisher=sportsnola.com|url=http://sportsnola.com/southlands-top-two-pitching-staffs-battle-ray-e-didier-field-weekend/|accessdate=2015-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Morales amazes at Didier|publisher=The Daily Comet|url=http://www.dailycomet.com/article/20150513/OPINION01/150519857|accessdate=2015-09-07}}</ref> Opened in 1960, the venue has a capacity of 3,200 spectators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicholls Colonels Baseball|publisher=geauxcolonels.com|url=http://www.geauxcolonels.com/documents/2012/2/14/2012_Baseball_Media_Guide.pdf|accessdate=2013-03-13}}</ref> The field is named after [[Raymond Didier|Raymond E. Didier]], head baseball coach from 1964–1973 and [[athletic director]] from 1963–1978.<ref>{{cite web|title=Didier shaped Nicholls athletics, many lives|publisher=HoumaToday.com|url=http://www.houmatoday.com/article/20110716/sports/110719558#gsc.tab=0|accessdate=2011-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/acadiana/sports/ul_lafayette/article_f4cb2b24-508e-11e7-9279-ab479cd350d9.html|title=Longtime college coach Raymond Didier joins his brother Mel in the Louisiana Sports Hall of Fame|publisher=theadvocate.com|accessdate=2018-07-29}}</ref>
The grandstand features chairback seating and a pressbox. The team's covered batting cage is located directly adjacent to the stadium along the third base side of the ballpark.
