{{Malay name|Rosmini|Kahar}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Rosmini Kahar | fullname = Rosmini bin Haji Abdul Kahar | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|09|01|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Brunei]] | height = | position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[MS PDB]] | clubnumber = | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2001–2003 | caps1 = | goals1 = | clubs1 = [[MS PDB|Police Force]] | years2 = 2001–2005 | caps2 = | goals2 = 1| clubs2 = [[Brunei (Malaysia Premier League team)|Brunei]] | years3 = 2003–2007 | caps3 = | goals3 = | clubs3 = [[Brunei DPMM FC|DPMM]] | years4 = 2008–2011 | caps4 = | goals4 = | clubs4 = [[AM Gunners]] | years5 = 2012–2014 | caps5 = | goals5 = 18| clubs5 = [[MS PDB]] | years6 = 2017– | caps6 = | goals6 = 2| clubs6 = [[MS PDB]] | nationalyears1= 2001 | nationalcaps1= 2 | nationalgoals1= 0 | nationalteam1= [[Brunei national under-23 football team|Brunei U23]] | nationalyears2= 2001 | nationalcaps2= 6 | nationalgoals2= 0 | nationalteam2= [[Brunei national football team|Brunei]] | club-update = 7 August 2017 | ntupdate = 5 January 2017 }}
[[Corporal]] '''Rosmini bin Haji Abdul Kahar''' (born 1 September 1979) is a [[Brunei]]an [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Royal Brunei Police Sports Council|MS PDB]] as a [[Midfielder (association football)|midfielder]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Football - Brunei soccer teams unveiled|url=http://www.e-borneo.com/cgi-bin/np/viewnews.cgi?category=2&id=986357099|date=4 April 2001|publisher=[[Borneo Bulletin]]|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> He also played in the [[Malaysian football league system|Malaysian leagues]] for the [[Brunei (Malaysia Premier League team)|Brunei M-League representative team]] and later [[Brunei DPMM FC]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Perak FC Juara Grup di Depan 200 Penonton|url=http://www.suaramerdeka.com/harian/0307/16/ora4.htm|date=16 July 2003|publisher=[[Suara Merdeka]]|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>
==Club career== Rosmini, a career policeman, played as a left-sided midfielder for the football team of the [[Royal Brunei Police Force]]. His performances in the international scene caught the eye of [[Mick Jones (footballer, born 1947)|Mick Jones]] who drafted him into the [[Brunei (Malaysia Premier League team)|Brunei M-League squad]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=M-League - Norsillmy, Rosmini to bolster Brunei|url=http://www.e-borneo.com/cgi-bin/np/viewnews.cgi?category=2&id=991371837|date=1 June 2001|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> He scarcely played for the Wasps due to work commitments and his preference to play at domestic club level for [[Brunei DPMM FC]] who signed him in 2003.<ref name="eteamz">{{cite web|url=http://www.eteamz.com/dpmmfc/news/|publisher=eteamz.com|title=DPMM FC: My Site News|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> He won the [[Brunei Premier League]] in [[2004 Brunei Premier League|2004]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Oct04/141004/nite19.htm|title=Undefeated DPMM FC Takes Home Crown|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|date=14 October 2004|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050107001810/http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Oct04/141004/nite19.htm|archivedate=7 January 2005|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> His solitary goal for Brunei came in a 1–1 draw against [[Kedah FA|Kedah]] on 20 March 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Malaysia 2005|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/malay05.html|date=1 July 2006|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref>
A year later, Rosmini's club moved to the [[Malaysia Premier League]] for the [[2005–06 Malaysia Premier League|2005–06 season]] to replace Brunei.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Dec05/031205/nite21.htm|title=Brunei DPMM FC Players Sign Contract |publisher=Borneo Bulletin|date=5 December 2005|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051205004846/http://www.brudirect.com/DailyInfo/News/Archive/Dec05/031205/nite21.htm|archivedate=5 December 2005|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> DPMM immediately won promotion, and in [[2006–07 Malaysia Super League|the following season]], finished third in Malaysia's top tier. Unfortunately, he was axed along with [[Affendy Akup]] and [[Zulkefly Duraman]] to make way for four Malaysian players in the [[2007–08 Malaysia Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2007/10/17/dpmm_fc_players_return_to_serious_training_for_msl|title=DPMM FC players return to serious training for MSL|publisher=[[The Brunei Times]]|date=17 October 2007|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415185547/http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2007/10/17/dpmm_fc_players_return_to_serious_training_for_msl|archivedate=15 April 2015|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>
Rosmini joined newly formed [[AM Gunners]] in the 2008 Brunei Premier Two and became league champions, gaining promotion to the top flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2008/04/21/gunners_ranger_through|title=Gunners, Ranger through|publisher=The Brunei Times|date=21 April 2008|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307210605/http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2008/04/21/gunners_ranger_through|archivedate=7 March 2016|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> AM Gunners left the Bruneian football league system in 2011 after two seasons. Rosmini next moved to and captained a reformed [[Majlis Sukan Polis Diraja Brunei|MS PDB]], returning to his first club in some ways.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fitness key to MS ABDB's victory against MS PDB |url=http://msabdbft.blogspot.com/2012/12/fitness-key-to-ms-abdbs-victory-against.html|date=15 December 2012|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> After a two-season hiatus, he re-appeared for the Policemen in the [[2017 Brunei Super League|2017 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kasuka FC sekadar seri dengan MS PDB |url=http://www.pelitabrunei.gov.bn/Lists/Berita/NewDisplayForm.aspx?ID=11336&ContentTypeId=0x0100BC31BF6D2ED1E4459ACCF88DA3E23BA8|date=8 July 2017|publisher=Pelita Brunei|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref>
==International career== Rosmini made his international debut for [[Brunei national football team|Brunei]] at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2002 World Cup qualifying round for Asia]] in a 0-5 loss against [[Yemen national football team|Yemen]], coming on to replace fellow policeman [[Jasriman Johari]] on 7 April 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3847/matches/match=20922/report.html|title=2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan ™ Preliminaries Brunei Darussalam - Yemen |publisher=FIFA.com|date=|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224041617/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3847/matches/match=20922/report.html|archivedate=24 February 2013|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> He started the rest of the qualifying matches as Brunei completed six games without scoring a goal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei's World Cup campaign ends in five-goal rout in India|url=http://www.e-borneo.com/cgi-bin/np/viewnews.cgi?category=2&id=990419321|date=21 May 2001|publisher=Borneo Bulletin|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref> Brunei subsequently refused to take part in World Cup qualifying until the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brunei to compete in World Cup qualifiers|url=http://www.nfabd.org/news/2015020301.htm|date=3 February 2015|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>
Rosmini also played two games for the [[Brunei national under-23 football team|Brunei under-23s]] at the [[Football at the 2001 Southeast Asian Games|21st SEA Games]] held in [[Malaysia]] in September 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=South East Asian Games 2001 (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) - Match Details|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/sea01-det.html|date=20 September 2001|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>
